The Corsair's Cove
A Skyrim One-Shot Adventure for 3-4 Players (Novice Tier)
Estimated Play Time: 2ΓÇô3 Hours
Party Size: 3-4 players
Difficulty: Scaled for Novice Tier (0 AP)
Reward: 500 Gold per player, the unique ZenitharΓÇÖs Bargain amulet, and 1 Advancement Point.

Adventure Summary
The party is hired by Orthus Endario, a desperate official of the East Empire Company in Solitude. A notorious pirate crew known as the Blackwater Marauders has seized a Company ship, The Red Sabre, and run it aground inside their hidden base at Broken Oar Grotto.
The ship carried a diplomatic gift intended for a powerful Thane: ZenitharΓÇÖs Bargain, an ancient amulet said to turn flesh to gold. Orthus needs the amulet recovered before his superiors discover the loss. The party must infiltrate the sea cave, navigate treacherous walkways above deep water, and defeat the pirate captain who has already claimed the amuletΓÇÖs power for himself.
This adventure emphasizes environmental tactics (pushing enemies into water), verticality (fighting on rigging and docks), and humanoid combat (intelligent enemies who use cover and coordination).

City Profile Stub: Solitude Docks
High Concept: The bustling, salt-sprayed commercial hub of the capital. While the city above is regal and orderly, the docks are a chaotic maze of crates, sailors, and shifting tides.
Atmosphere: The cry of gulls is constant. The smell of fish, tar, and exotic spices fills the air. It is a place of business, but also a place where things "fall off the back of a cart" with alarming frequency.
Core Conflict: "Profit vs. Piracy." The East Empire Company tries to maintain a monopoly, but independent pirate crews like the Blackwater Marauders constantly nip at their heels, emboldened by the distraction of the Civil War.

Part I: The Solitude Docks (The Hook)
Sub-Part A: The Nervous Administrator
Setting the Scene
The adventure begins on the bustling docks of Solitude. It is a gray, blustery morning. The cries of gulls compete with the shouting of dockworkers, and the smell of fish, tar, and salt is overwhelming. While the city above stands proud and orderly, the docks are a maze of crates, ropes, and shifting shadows.
Read Aloud:
"The shadow of the great stone arch of Solitude looms high above you, but down here on the water, the world is chaotic and loud. The East Empire Company docks are a hive of activity, but your contact isn't meeting you in a warm office. You were told to find him at the end of a rotting pier, far away from the prying eyes of the main harbor guards.
There, pacing nervously back and forth, is an Imperial man dressed in fine velvet robes that are woefully unsuited for the sea spray. He clutches a waterproof leather satchel to his chest like a shield, and he jumps slightly as you approach. This is Orthus Endario, and he looks like a man whose life is about to end."
The Quest Giver: Orthus Endario
Role: Junior Administrator for the East Empire Company.
Stats: Non-combatant (Guile 12).
Demeanor: Panicked, desperate, and sweating despite the cold wind. He speaks quickly, constantly checking over his shoulder to see if his superiors are watching.
Dialogue Script: The Proposal
(Orthus rushes forward, speaking in a hushed, urgent tone.)
"You came. Thank the Divines. I was afraid you were Company auditors. Listen, we don't have much time. I need people who can handle a sword and keep their mouths shut, and I'm told that's you."
(He gestures to the open sea.)
"Three hours ago, a Company transport, The Red Sabre, was seized just outside the harbor. Pirates. The Blackwater Marauders. They didn't sink itΓÇöthey ran it aground inside their hideout at Broken Oar Grotto to strip it for parts."
(He leans in closer, his voice dropping to a whisper.)
"The cargo... the cargo is insured. I don't care about the silk or the spices. But there was a small lockbox in the captain's quarters. Inside is a diplomatic gift intended for a very powerful Thane in Markarth. An amulet. Zenithar's Bargain."
"If my superiors find out I lost a relic of that value to a pack of dirty corsairs, I won't just lose my job. I'll be scrubbing dungeon floors in Castle Dour for the rest of my life. I need you to get it back. I will pay 500 Gold Septims to each of youΓÇöoff the books, completely tax-freeΓÇöif you bring me that amulet before the sun sets."
Sub-Part B: The Journey & The Briefing
The Skiff Ride
Orthus ushers the party into a small, nondescript fishing skiff rowed by a silent, grim-faced sailor paid to ask no questions. As the skiff cuts through the choppy waves of the Sea of Ghosts, Orthus provides the tactical briefing.
Read Aloud:
"The small boat pitches and rolls in the cold water, spray soaking your cloaks. Orthus sits opposite you, looking green in the face, wiping seafoam from his expensive tunic with a silk handkerchief. He practically has to shout to be heard over the crashing waves."
Dialogue Script: The Intel
(Orthus grips the gunwale of the boat, knuckles white.)
"The place you're going... Broken Oar Grotto. It's a massive sea cave about two miles north. The Marauders use it because it's too shallow for Company galleons to follow them in. But this skiff can get you to the entrance."
(If asked about the opposition):
"They are led by a Redguard named Captain Valen. They call him 'Iron-Lung' because he never seems to tire. He's a duelistΓÇöfast, vain, and arrogant. He loves gold more than his own mother. If he found the lockbox, he's almost certainly wearing the amulet already. He won't know what it does, only that it looks expensive."
(If asked about the Amulet's powers):
"It's not just jewelry! It's an ancient enchanted relic blessed by the God of Commerce. Legend says it can turn flesh as hard as gold to protect the wearer from harm. If Valen figures out how to trigger it... well, just hit him hard and hit him fast."
Sub-Part C: The Arrival (The Drop Off)
The Maw of the Grotto
The journey is short but rough. After twenty minutes of rowing, the skiff rounds a jagged spire of rock, revealing the destination.
Read Aloud:
"Ahead, the cliff face seems to have been smashed open by a giant's hammer. Broken Oar Grotto is a massive, gaping wound in the stone, swallowing the ocean into its darkness. The sound of the waves echoing inside sounds like the breathing of a great beast.
High above the cave mouth, you see crude wooden pikes mounted on the rocksΓÇöskulls bleaching in the salt air. A warning to anyone foolish enough to approach.
The sailor ships his oars and lets the skiff drift toward a natural rocky shelf just inside the entrance, obscured from the deeper cave by a wall of stalagmites. The water here is dark and calm, contrasting with the violence of the open sea."
Dialogue Script: The Send-Off
(Orthus scrambles to keep his balance as the boat bumps against the rock. He refuses to step off.)
"This is as close as we go. I... I am an administrator, not a warrior. I would only slow you down."
"I will wait here with the boat. Please, be careful. These Marauders are vicious, and the cave is treacherous. But remember: The Amulet. Nothing else matters."
The Transition
The party steps off the wet rocks onto the natural stone shelf. The air changes instantlyΓÇöfrom the fresh, cold wind of the sea to the humid, stagnant smell of the cave: rotting wood, wet fur, and unwashed bodies. Ahead, the natural rock gives way to wooden planks.
GM Note: The party is now at the entrance to Section 1. They are hidden by stalagmites, giving them a moment to assess the situation before engaging.

Part III: Broken Oar Grotto
Section 1: The Sentry Dock (The Guardian)
The Setting
The party emerges from behind the stalagmites onto the edge of the pirateΓÇÖs domain. The cave opens up into a massive, cathedral-like cavern filled with sea water. The ceiling is lost in shadows, but hanging braziers cast a flickering orange glow over the scene.
Read Aloud:
"The air here is thick and humid, smelling of wet wood and unwashed bodies. You are standing on a natural rock shelf that connects to a hastily constructed wooden dock system suspended over the churning water.
About forty feet ahead, the dock widens into a checkpoint. A heavy wooden gate blocks the path deeper into the cave. Two piratesΓÇöBlackwater SentriesΓÇöare sitting on crates, lazily rolling dice and passing a bottle of rum between them.
Above them, a repurpsosed shipΓÇÖs mast has been driven into the seabed to serve as a watchtower. A third pirate sits in the crowΓÇÖs nest, thirty feet up, idly sharpening arrows and scanning the water, though he seems more interested in the dice game below than his duty."
