Section 3: The Beast Pen (The Setback)
The Setting
The tunnel opens into a natural, sandy cavern that serves as the pirates' rough storage area. Crates of stolen trade goodsΓÇöfine silks, Iron Ingots, and sacks of grainΓÇöare stacked haphazardly against the walls. The air here is pungent, smelling of wet fur, raw meat, and animal waste.
Dominating the center of the room is a makeshift cage built from ship timbers reinforced with iron bands. Inside, something massive paces restlessly.
Read Aloud:
"You step onto soft sand. This chamber is a mess of stolen cargo, but your attention is drawn immediately to the center of the room. A massive cage has been constructed here, and inside is a Cave Bear of terrifying size.
The beast is in a sorry state. It wears a crude leather eyepatch over one eye, and its fur is matted with salt and tar. It paces the small enclosure, letting out low, rumbling growls that vibrate in your chest. The pirates have clearly been tormenting it for sport.
The path to the next section lies directly past the cage. However, you notice a tripwire stretched tight across the sand, connected to the pin holding the cage door shut. One wrong step, and that beast is loose."
The Trap: The release Mechanism
The pirates have rigged the cage to open if intruders stumble through the room, turning their pet into a guardian.
Spotting the Trap: A Standard Guile (Perception) check.
Disarming the Trap: A Standard Agility (Thievery) check to unhook the wire without pulling the pin.
Trigger: If the party fails the check or walks through without searching, the pin pulls free. The cage door crashes open.
The Enemy: "Barnacle" the Cave Bear
Rank: Novice Tier, TL 2 Lieutenant (Brute)
If released, the bear does not distinguish between friend or foeΓÇöit hates everything.
Stats: Might 16, Agility 10, Magic 6, Guile 8.
HP: 25 (A tough, meaty sponge for damage).
DR: 2 (Thick Fur and Scars).
Damage: 6 (Claws) or 8 (Bite - Deep Wounds).
Abilities:
Bear Hug: If both claw attacks hit (or on a Critical Success), the target is Grappled and takes an automatic 4 crushing damage at the start of their next turn.
Enraged: When reduced to 10 HP or less, Barnacle gains Advantage on all attack rolls.


Tactics:
Barnacle charges the nearest target with a roar. He fights with zero self-preservation. He is a wall of muscle and fur designed to drain the party's resources (HP/potions) before the boss.
Alternative Approaches (Non-Combat)
This encounter rewards creative players who notice the bear is abused rather than naturally evil.
The Wood Elf Solution: A Wood Elf player can use their Command Animal racial ability. This works automatically. Barnacle calms down and can even be commanded to guard the rear or attack the pirates in the next room.
The Magical Solution: An Illusionist can cast Calm. The bear sits down and begins eating a sack of stolen grain.
The Druidic Approach: A character with high Guile can attempt a Hard (-2) check to offer food (rations) and back away slowly. If successful, the bear chooses the food over the fight.
Loot & Transition
In the Cage: In the back of the bear's bedding is a skeletal hand wearing a Ring of Minor Stamina (+5 Max FP). The bear ate the last person who tried to feed it.
The Cargo: Searching the crates yields random trade goods (worth 50 gold if carried out) and a Potion of Fortify Might.
Transition:
Beyond the storage cave, the path slopes upward, turning back into wooden planks. You hear shouting, laughter, and the creak of a massive ship. You are approaching the flagship.

Section 4: The Deck of the Red Sabre (The Boss Fight)
The Setting
The wooden path rises steeply, connecting to the main gangplank of the grounded flagship. The Red Sabre is an East Empire galleon, its hull scarred but intact, wedged onto a rocky sandbar in the largest chamber of the Grotto. The deck is lit by torches, and you can see pirates working to strip the rigging.
Standing on the quarterdeck, shouting orders and drinking from a jeweled goblet, is Captain Valen.
Read Aloud:
"You emerge onto the main deck of The Red Sabre. The ship lists slightly to port, creaking under its own weight. The deck is a clutter of ropes, barrels, and dismantled cannons.
On the raised quarterdeck stands Captain Valen, known as 'Iron-Lung.' He is a massive Redguard with a shaved head and a beard braided with gold wire. He wears flashy silk clothes stolen from a dozen different ports, but the scimitars on his hips are strictly business. Around his neck, gleaming in the torchlight, is a heavy gold medallion set with a massive topazΓÇöZenithar's Bargain.
He spots you immediately and laughs, a booming sound that echoes off the cave walls. 'Company men? Or just vultures looking for scraps? No matter. YouΓÇÖll make fine shark bait! Get them, boys!'"
